A TEAM that wins the first trophy of the season, the MTN8, has the potential to finish the season successfully. With that belief, Thulani “Tyson” Hlatshwayo intends to guide Orlando Pirates to glory in the top-eight final and set the tone for the rest of the season. The former Bidvest Wits skipper is expected to guide the Soweto giants in their R8m Wafa Wafa final against Bloemfontein Celtic at Moses Mabhida Stadium in Durban on Saturday (6pm). But the cup final is more than the prize money and the glittering trophy for the Bucs skipper. “Everyone, including the new players, know that it’s all about success at Pirates,” said Hlatshwayo. “As a player, you have goals and targets that you want to achieve. I’ve said before that the team that wins the first trophy of the season, the MTN8, have the momentum to do well throughout the season. And that’s what we want to do as a team, as our target.” Unsuccessful in their last four knockout competition finals, the Buccaneers are hoping to end a six-year trophy drought. And Hlatshwayo knows the weight of expectations, which can’t be compared to that of his previous team, Wits. CONTINUED ON PAGE 30